{"term":"1972","caseName":"Neil v. Biggers","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1972/71-586","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 18, 1972","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16060","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll hear arguments next in 71-586, Neil against Biggers.","start":0,"stop":37.118,"duration":37.12},{"text":"Mr. Durham.","start":37.118,"stop":39.178,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":39.178,"stop":43.049,"duration":3.87},{"text":"This case here is on a petition for writ of certiorari to the Sixth Circuit in which two questions are raised.","start":43.049,"stop":50.74,"duration":7.69},{"text":"The first one is, in respect to a case that was here before and affirmed four-four by this Honorable Court.","start":50.74,"stop":59.229,"duration":8.49},{"text":"The second one is; the Stovall question as to whether or not this defendant had a fair pretrial confrontation.","start":59.229,"stop":69.014,"duration":9.78},{"text":"In order to give Your Honors a background, I'll state the chronology of the case, it was here in 1967 and ’68.","start":69.014,"stop":80.577,"duration":11.56},{"text":"The crime occurred in January of 1965.","start":80.577,"stop":84.86,"duration":4.28},{"text":"The defendant was identified at the police station in that year, and his subsequent trial and conviction was affirmed by the Tennessee Supreme Court in March of 1967.","start":84.86,"stop":99.095,"duration":14.24},{"text":"This Court granted certiorari, and the case was argued before this Court in January of 1968.","start":99.095,"stop":108.995,"duration":9.9},{"text":"Mr. Justice Marshall recused himself, and the Court after hearing plenary arguments, affirmed at the Tennessee Supreme Court which had affirmed the rape conviction by a vote of four-four.","start":108.995,"stop":123.595,"duration":14.6},{"text":"There was no written opinion from the Court, but Mr. Justice Douglas recorded the reasons for his dissent as one the four dissenters.","start":123.595,"stop":135.285,"duration":11.69},{"text":"Shortly after the case was affirmed in March of ’68, this defendant went right back into the Federal Court System by filing a petition for writ of habeas corpus, seeking to re-litigate what the state contends as -- was the same issue before the Federal District Judge in Nashville.","start":135.285,"stop":156.39,"duration":21.1},{"text":"A plenary – a limited evidentiary hearing was held, and the court found that the pretrial confrontation was violative of this Court’s principle in Stovall, and ordered a new trial unaffected by the valid identification.","start":156.39,"stop":174.845,"duration":18.46},{"text":"The state took in an appeal to the Sixth Circuit from the United States District Judge opinion, Honorable William E. Miller, who is now a member of the Sixth Circuit and, the Sixth Circuit by two to one division, Judges McRae, and Brook, and Edwards, in the majority with a lengthy dissent by (Inaudible) to Judge Brooks.","start":174.845,"stop":198.13,"duration":23.28},{"text":"That court affirmed the District Court from whence this Court has granted certiorari.","start":198.13,"stop":203.953,"duration":5.82},{"text":"So the two questions are; what is the effect of a four-four affirmance with respect to habeas corpus, and did the defendant have a prior pretrial identification?","start":203.953,"stop":215.046,"duration":11.09},{"text":"With respect to the first question, we think the law was quite clear and possibly conceded by, adversaries it says, that with respect to any other case except the habeas corpus case, a four-four affirmance ends the case, as between the parties, and as to that matter.","start":215.046,"stop":234.875,"duration":19.83},{"text":"Some distinction has been made by the Federal District Court, because this is not an ordinary civil case, it involves human liberties, and we think of the higher position in our jurisprudence which habeas corpus hold.","start":234.875,"stop":251.878,"duration":17},{"text":"But, we say that historically and traditionally, there has to be an end to litigation, and that it should have ended this case.","start":251.878,"stop":261.945,"duration":10.07},{"text":"But our primary contention with respect to this, is an act of Congress, 28 U.S.C. Title 2244 (c).","start":261.945,"stop":270.748,"duration":8.8},{"text":"That statute provides and that’s what we’re relying on here, it is found at page 3 of my brief, that that statute was drawn specifically to provide for finality of determination.","start":270.748,"stop":289.137,"duration":18.39},{"text":"When a case has been to this Court and been -- a judgment of this Court, it says, “Shall be conclusive as to all issues which were before this court.”","start":289.137,"stop":298.651,"duration":9.51},{"text":"And we cite the legislative history of that statute, as well as commentary in the Harvard Law Review and others, in which we feel it’s clear that Judge Oren Harris of the Tenth Circuit in his letter --","start":298.651,"stop":313.508,"duration":14.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But Mr. Durham, I gather you have to argue the significance of what actually the Court adjudicated, don’t you?","start":313.508,"stop":323.281,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, Your Honor.","start":323.281,"stop":325.354,"duration":2.07},{"text":"That’s --","start":325.354,"stop":325.627,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And really, I suppose under the statute.","start":325.627,"stop":327.65,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg --","start":327.65,"stop":327.899,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is a four-four, is that disposition actually adjudicated?","start":327.899,"stop":334.556,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":334.556,"stop":335.672,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And do you -- you know, at least I have been able to find much help in the legislative history to support your argument.","start":335.672,"stop":342.959,"duration":7.29},{"text":"Do you find any?","start":342.959,"stop":345.097,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I think -- no sir, I don’t find anything particular -- exactly other than that --","start":345.097,"stop":357.605,"duration":12.51}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it does have the tape between the parties.","start":357.605,"stop":361.26,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"We think that it ends the case between the parties as to that issue.","start":361.26,"stop":366.838,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) Yeah, it is an adjudication between the parties.","start":366.838,"stop":369.107,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"As to that issue.","start":369.107,"stop":370.599,"duration":1.49},{"text":"If that be the law, then our arguments won.","start":370.599,"stop":375.811,"duration":5.21},{"text":"But does it – we cited it ends the case between the parties as to that issue.","start":375.811,"stop":382.03,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you say that it’s just like a five to four, or a nine to nothing, except as to the precedential value of the reason?","start":382.03,"stop":389.836,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, yes sir, Your Honor.","start":389.836,"stop":396.104,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You said it was true in ordinary litigation, in the absence of the statute, you’d be faced with a proposition, wouldn’t you, that there is no res judicata in habeas corpus.","start":396.104,"stop":410.342,"duration":14.24}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":410.342,"stop":412.395,"duration":2.05},{"text":"There is no res judicata in habeas corpus, except Congress has said that --","start":412.395,"stop":416.587,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I say, absent the statute.","start":416.587,"stop":418.032,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, excuse me, that's different.","start":418.032,"stop":419.452,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":419.452,"stop":420.521,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"That's because it's common law, there was no appeal in habeas -- in the habeas corpus.","start":420.521,"stop":424.053,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, whatever the reason, it's well settled I thought.","start":424.053,"stop":426.673,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":426.673,"stop":427.349,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Tell me if I’m wrong that ordinary concepts of res judicata are simply inapplicable to habeas corpus proceedings.","start":427.349,"stop":434.437,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":434.437,"stop":435.027,"duration":0.59},{"text":"And the reason I suppose I think --","start":435.027,"stop":436.229,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And that’s the reason as I understand that you’re relying so heavily on this statute.","start":436.229,"stop":440.461,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":440.461,"stop":441.176,"duration":0.71},{"text":"And I’m going behind that explaining the reason that -- if that law is it -- but there is no res judicata was because there was no appeal.","start":441.176,"stop":447.926,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":447.926,"stop":449.009,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Durham, supposing in this case instead of the four-four affirmance there had been as the Chief Justice suggested a moment ago, an affirmance on the merits by nine to nothing, eight to one, some rather lopsided majority.","start":449.009,"stop":468.044,"duration":19.03},{"text":"What is your opinion as to whether a federal habeas on these same issues would then lie in the District Court for this particular petition?","start":468.044,"stop":475.299,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my opinion Your Honor is that the District Judge would recognize this Court’s case law, and would've found -- would have refused to entertain the case, as well as it's controlled by the same statute.","start":475.299,"stop":490.325,"duration":15.03}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You say then in effect that although as between lower court decisions, there may be no res judicata in federal habeas, if this Court has once affirmed on the merits, that ends not only the direct litigation, but further habeas corpus.","start":490.325,"stop":504.014,"duration":13.69}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":504.014,"stop":504.471,"duration":0.46},{"text":"We think that the case law is --","start":504.471,"stop":506.416,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"In the absence of new client?","start":506.416,"stop":507.915,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":507.915,"stop":509.778,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though between the same parties?","start":509.778,"stop":511.563,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":511.563,"stop":513.025,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And even though the same constitutional provision is invoked?","start":513.025,"stop":515.809,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":515.809,"stop":516.908,"duration":1.1},{"text":"There can be a new like the Burton Rule or something might come up which Your Honors suggest on the case law makes those changes.","start":516.908,"stop":526.083,"duration":9.17},{"text":"Now, as Mr. Justice Brennan said, “The legislative was history to the extent that there is any and hidden much as in -- exactly clear.”","start":526.083,"stop":536.056,"duration":9.97},{"text":"But we did feel, that what little there is, does support our position.","start":536.056,"stop":541.052,"duration":5},{"text":"However, we are not -- by succeeding doing nothing more in my oral argument today, I do want to stress the second point of our contention, and that is on the facts, the District judge grievously erred in finding that there was a bad confrontation.","start":541.052,"stop":563.126,"duration":22.07},{"text":"The -- ordinarily, I’m aware this Court wouldn’t want to go into the facts, where the District Court has found facts, and Appellate Court has affirmed it, and I’m asking Your Honors to look again at the facts.","start":563.126,"stop":576.547,"duration":13.42},{"text":"But the point is that the District Judge didn’t hear any new facts and he didn’t weigh the credibility of evidence.","start":576.547,"stop":585.244,"duration":8.7},{"text":"We say that he made seven grievous sins.","start":585.244,"stop":589.587,"duration":4.34},{"text":"We cite five of those at page 34 of our brief, and in addition of those five, earlier we mentioned the error that the District Judge made when he said that the victim changed her story, and between the time of the trial and the habeas corpus hearing, and that the police officer changed his story between the time of the trial in the habeas corpus hearing and that just isn’t simply so.","start":589.587,"stop":615.544,"duration":25.96},{"text":"The fact of the matter is, the lineup was held.","start":615.544,"stop":622.722,"duration":7.18},{"text":"There were only three people who testified about the lineup and I’m talking about the original trial record now.","start":622.722,"stop":630.11,"duration":7.39},{"text":"Those policemen were Detective Smith, Lieutenant Daniel and Detective Bailey.","start":630.11,"stop":635.033,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Detective Smith at page 40 of the record, and Detective Bailey at page 48 of the record, said that this victim identified the man before she heard him speak.","start":635.033,"stop":647.726,"duration":12.69},{"text":"And that she thereafter asked him to speak merely to confirm her identification.","start":647.726,"stop":654.232,"duration":6.51},{"text":"I say in this, and I make an analogy in my brief as one of the judges in the lower court did in Stovall, what would be the argument had that lady in Stovall case died, and they not taking the man over there to view Mrs. Barrett, the victim in that case.","start":654.232,"stop":671.075,"duration":16.84},{"text":"So, they brought --","start":671.075,"stop":672.829,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose there was the difference.","start":672.829,"stop":674.489,"duration":1.66},{"text":"As I recall it in Stovall, the victim was an extreme, they didn’t think she was going to survive the night.","start":674.489,"stop":680.76,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":680.76,"stop":681.261,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But I gather that wasn't the case here, was it?","start":681.261,"stop":683.151,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no sir.","start":683.151,"stop":683.796,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":683.796,"stop":685.186,"duration":1.39},{"text":"The victim, as I remember the facts, viewed the young man at the police station many, many months, was that after the actual crime.","start":685.186,"stop":695.718,"duration":10.53}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Sir.","start":695.718,"stop":696.176,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And no problem about her health or anything else, suggested then was --","start":696.176,"stop":700.048,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"The trial counsel --","start":700.048,"stop":700.766,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":700.766,"stop":701.742,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time this case was decided, no American Court that I’m aware of had ever held that the identification was anything other than a question of weight and not admissibility.","start":701.742,"stop":712.109,"duration":10.37},{"text":"The weight even lower court cases were to come later.","start":712.109,"stop":716.827,"duration":4.72},{"text":"This was in January -- August of 1965.","start":716.827,"stop":721.268,"duration":4.44},{"text":"So the State believes that the record is un-contradicted, that the facts were that she identified them first, all the parties were black, the defendant was in the company of two black officers, she made -- the victim made this identification, then she requested that he speak.","start":721.268,"stop":742.783,"duration":21.51},{"text":"Even the victim himself in his affidavit at the federal habeas hearing doesn't -- his affidavit we cite don't contradict it.","start":742.783,"stop":751.645,"duration":8.86},{"text":"No, the third officer who testified about the lineup was the Supervising Officer, Lt. McDaniel.","start":751.645,"stop":757.342,"duration":5.7},{"text":"And it’s unclear from his trial testimony, whether she identified him first or heard him speak first.","start":757.342,"stop":764.592,"duration":7.25},{"text":"But at the habeas hearing, he -- his memory had been refreshed.","start":764.592,"stop":768.806,"duration":4.21},{"text":"But we say, it wasn’t the point at the trial testimony, who cared?","start":768.806,"stop":772.151,"duration":3.34},{"text":"Nobody asked on cross-examination, nobody brought it out, whether she heard him speak first or she didn’t.","start":772.151,"stop":779.232,"duration":7.08},{"text":"And those are the five errors as I say, I’ve listed in the page, beginning at page 34 of my brief as just factual errors which the District Court, just made an error on.","start":779.232,"stop":799.291,"duration":20.06},{"text":"In defense of the district judge, let me say that I’m the fifth or sixth attorney who’s handled this case for the state, and when the habeas petition was filed, the factual aspects were shuffled off in the second place, because the state felt that as a matter of law that we should have prevailed based on my first argument.","start":799.291,"stop":823.679,"duration":24.39},{"text":"So these facts were never really strenuously argued to the District Court, but they are un-contradicted in this 1965 transcript.","start":823.679,"stop":833.79,"duration":10.11},{"text":"And we point out that by analogy to some of the other lineup or rather one on one confrontation cases which this Court has made that we believe this lineup is as far as is constitutionally impermissible than others.","start":833.79,"stop":849.643,"duration":15.85},{"text":"I conclude.","start":849.643,"stop":851.279,"duration":1.64},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":851.279,"stop":853.986,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Durham.","start":853.986,"stop":857.273,"duration":3.29},{"text":"Mr. Meltsner.","start":857.273,"stop":860.932,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":860.932,"stop":864.838,"duration":3.91},{"text":"It is far from accidental that with respect to the consequence of a four-four affirmance, the State relies on the statute here.","start":864.838,"stop":877.961,"duration":13.12},{"text":"It goes -- its position of that a four-four affirmance would bar an initial federal habeas corpus petition claiming a denial of due process, fails to come to terms with several principles which have been quite prominent in this Court’s decisions in the area.","start":877.961,"stop":896.704,"duration":18.74},{"text":"The first is that a state court’s disposition of a state prisoner’s federal constitutional question is not a conclusive determination of that question, and that each state prisoner will at least have one opportunity to obtain a resolution of this federal constitutional claim in a federal forum.","start":896.704,"stop":921.065,"duration":24.36},{"text":"When this Court affirms by an equal division, it merely leaves standing a state court determination of federal question, whatever it is.","start":921.065,"stop":930.595,"duration":9.53},{"text":"Indeed one can imagine quite easily the Court affirming by an equal division to totally inconsistent lower court decisions.","start":930.595,"stop":943.069,"duration":12.47},{"text":"Yet, the position taken by the state here would convert this state court disposition of a federal constitutional question into an absolute bar that will be habeas corpus.","start":943.069,"stop":953.971,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Will the situation be any different Mr. Meltsner if suppose where a grant here asserted on direct review --","start":953.971,"stop":965.692,"duration":11.72}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":965.692,"stop":965.997,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of the State Court decision, and we divided four-four to affirm the conviction brought here by the state prison.","start":965.997,"stop":975.729,"duration":9.73},{"text":"Is there this difference in that situation --","start":975.729,"stop":978.881,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":978.881,"stop":979.159,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as to the availability of federal habeas from the situation we have here, which is a four-four affirmance act or grant of cert -- to a -- and a federal habeas?","start":979.159,"stop":991.331,"duration":12.17}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"If I understand your question correctly Mr. Justice Brennan, the difference is that in this situation Congress has decided to make federal habeas corpus available to the petitioner for collateral attack.","start":991.331,"stop":1004.024,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"At (Inaudible) where this Court has actually (Voice Overlap) --","start":1004.024,"stop":1007.026,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually decided.","start":1007.026,"stop":1008.226,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that’s my question.","start":1008.226,"stop":1008.754,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1008.754,"stop":1009.19,"duration":0.44},{"text":"Which --","start":1009.19,"stop":1009.38,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming this statute, this statute would apply I take it, whether or not require a determination to whether there was some actual adjudication.","start":1009.38,"stop":1018.423,"duration":9.04},{"text":"Whether or not our four-four division was on direct review of the state conviction, or was a four-four division on a one federal habeas review?","start":1018.423,"stop":1028.28,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"The only difference would be that again, if I understand your question that in the latter situation, suppose this Court would have four-four affirmed this case at this point --","start":1028.28,"stop":1037.097,"duration":8.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well – what it will be four on habeas, was it --?","start":1037.097,"stop":1039.242,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it was here on direct review.","start":1039.242,"stop":1040.272,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":1040.272,"stop":1040.417,"duration":0.14},{"text":"Was it direct review?","start":1040.417,"stop":1041.16,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"A direct review.","start":1041.16,"stop":1041.896,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.(Voice Overlap)","start":1041.896,"stop":1042.304,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"But if this court were to four-four affirm now --","start":1042.304,"stop":1045.276,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1045.276,"stop":1045.568,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at least there would be a federal court’s determination of the federal question standing.","start":1045.568,"stop":1051.107,"duration":5.54},{"text":"And one of the statutes involved in the case, 2109, of the Judicial Code makes quite clear that in Congress’ contemplation at least, the highest court that can determine this question ought to determine it where this Court is disabled, because of a four-four split from hearing it.","start":1051.107,"stop":1073.152,"duration":22.05},{"text":"The second principle though --","start":1073.152,"stop":1073.913,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Meltsner, do you feel --","start":1073.913,"stop":1075.001,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We aren't disabled from hearing it.","start":1075.001,"stop":1077.54,"duration":2.54},{"text":"We have --","start":1077.54,"stop":1077.731,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"From deciding it, Mr. Chief Justice, from deciding it.","start":1077.731,"stop":1082.195,"duration":4.46},{"text":"This Court has consistently said that what a four-four affirmance is, is what a technical rule of judicial administration, it’s an action out of necessity, it’s something that the Court does because it cannot do anything else.","start":1082.195,"stop":1096.235,"duration":14.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I guess that was Chief Justice Marshall’s quite language, wasn’t it?","start":1096.235,"stop":1100.99,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s close to it --","start":1100.99,"stop":1102.573,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1102.573,"stop":1102.665,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the first case that the --","start":1102.665,"stop":1105.184,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The court’s inability to decide it --","start":1105.184,"stop":1107.095,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1107.095,"stop":1107.218,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that it requires the four-four affirmance.","start":1107.218,"stop":1108.727,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1108.727,"stop":1109.594,"duration":0.87},{"text":"I think that --","start":1109.594,"stop":1110.128,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Meltsner, you feel then that the four-four affirmance in the circumstances that was here below, is a different situation than say at seven to two affirmance with an opinion on the merits.","start":1110.128,"stop":1122.588,"duration":12.46}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"On question --","start":1122.588,"stop":1123.148,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As I said in the --","start":1123.148,"stop":1123.87,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"The question here and the Court has made its decision by a majority in that case.","start":1123.87,"stop":1129.165,"duration":5.3},{"text":"I do not think --","start":1129.165,"stop":1130.287,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But if habeas -- if habeas corpus isn’t res judicata, why should a decision on the merits by this Court foreclose a potential habeas petitioner any more than a decision of a lower court?","start":1130.287,"stop":1143.049,"duration":12.76}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think using the label res judicata is somewhat misleading.","start":1143.049,"stop":1147.577,"duration":4.53},{"text":"Even in Sanders versus the United States, the Court said, “There were some principles of finality which govern the habeas corpus jurisdiction.”","start":1147.577,"stop":1155.985,"duration":8.41},{"text":"But they were to be employed by use of equitable principles.","start":1155.985,"stop":1159.605,"duration":3.62},{"text":"And Sanders sets forth situation where let's say, abuse of the writ is involved, where a federal district court can say, “No, I am not going to determine this question.”","start":1159.605,"stop":1170.122,"duration":10.52},{"text":"Of course, another court has heard and decided.","start":1170.122,"stop":1172.549,"duration":2.43},{"text":"Now, whether it's called res judicata or stare decisis or a principle of finality, I don’t think there's a District Judge inland who would re-litigate a question which was fully considered by this Court ,and decided by this Court unless they were either a change in law or new factual -- material factual matter that was presented, which made the federal constitutional question a different one, in kind, from the one this Court decided.","start":1172.549,"stop":1202.07,"duration":29.52},{"text":"Now, I do not believe that res judicata or any principle of finality would jurisdictionally bar a Federal District Court from considering a habeas petition in that circumstance.","start":1202.07,"stop":1215.565,"duration":13.5},{"text":"But absent those circumstances, it’s plain to me that there would be no -- there would be no -- there will be no equity in the petition, and that it would not be heard.","start":1215.565,"stop":1225.616,"duration":10.05},{"text":"Now, it's interesting that the statute which the state here relies on heavily in light of the principle I mentioned, and also in light of the general principle that technical adjudication is used, short of the merits are not sufficient to bar federal habeas corpus.","start":1225.616,"stop":1246.848,"duration":21.23},{"text":"The procedural rules emanating from the process of direct review do not bar federal habeas corpus, unless they amount to a deliberate bypass or an actual determination of federal question, the state comes to the statute.","start":1246.848,"stop":1260.56,"duration":13.71},{"text":"Now there is nothing in the legislative history that suggests that Congress sought to deal with this problem, and it's this deal in my judgment that suggests the contrary.","start":1260.56,"stop":1272.033,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there an actual judgment as a result of a four to four division of the Court?","start":1272.033,"stop":1277.609,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the judgment of the -- my understanding is the judgment of the court below is affirmed in the same way that the process of direct review is ended when this Court denied cert.","start":1277.609,"stop":1288.471,"duration":10.86}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And the language of the statute is actually adjudicated?","start":1288.471,"stop":1291.084,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually adjudicated (Voice Overlap) --","start":1291.084,"stop":1292.837,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And how do -- if there's an actual judgment, isn’t it actually adjudicated?","start":1292.837,"stop":1298.674,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think what is clearly intended is that there is a decision on the merits of the question.","start":1298.674,"stop":1305.493,"duration":6.82},{"text":"And the statute would make little sense if that language was not read that way, because in a statute after stating that an actual adjudication will bar subsequent relief by habeas corpus, the statute goes on to define that situation where a new material of fact has been alleged, and it was not avoided in the past because of lack of due diligence, and describes that in that situation federal habeas corpus will, --","start":1305.493,"stop":1341.378,"duration":35.88}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What if the statute just said a judgment instead of actually adjudicated?","start":1341.378,"stop":1347.712,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"If it said a judgment, we would have it at least, as far as the statute is concerned, we’d have a somewhat different case, because there's no explanation for the use of the word actual in this statute, unless Congress meant something more than technical affirmance of the sort we’re dealing with here.","start":1347.712,"stop":1365.505,"duration":17.79},{"text":"Now Congress has passed in 2109 of the Judicial Code, a statute which expressly equates the lack of a forum by this Court with a four-four affirmance.","start":1365.505,"stop":1376.075,"duration":10.57},{"text":"There is nothing whatsoever in the legislative history of the statute to suggest that Congress sought to change its understanding of what a four-four affirmance meant.","start":1376.075,"stop":1385.459,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Couldn’t it have been suggesting perhaps that a denial of certiorari was not an actual adjudication?","start":1385.459,"stop":1391.738,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that’s --","start":1391.738,"stop":1393.016,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"One that --","start":1393.016,"stop":1393.259,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"-- clearly what the draftsmen of the statute had in mind.","start":1393.259,"stop":1395.463,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well actually, there is -- there is some legislative history supporting that Mr. Meltsner.(Voice Overlap)","start":1395.463,"stop":1399.4,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, of course.","start":1399.4,"stop":1400.181,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And yes, you know.","start":1400.181,"stop":1401.045,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course there is.","start":1401.045,"stop":1402.206,"duration":1.16},{"text":"And a denial of certiorari as I’ve indicated has no precedential value.","start":1402.206,"stop":1406.792,"duration":4.59},{"text":"It ends the process of direct review, and it does not bar a subsequent habeas corpus jurisdiction this time.","start":1406.792,"stop":1413.225,"duration":6.43},{"text":"And I think the functional effect of a four-four affirmance is and ought to be the same.","start":1413.225,"stop":1419.196,"duration":5.97},{"text":"Additionally, the legislative history can be as it is, suggests that the problem that the Congress was concerned with was abuse of the writ, was re-litigation of it -- of questions that had actually been decided.","start":1419.196,"stop":1433.465,"duration":14.27},{"text":"There's nothing of that sort here.","start":1433.465,"stop":1437.962,"duration":4.5},{"text":"Cases arising at a four-four affirmances are hardly flooding the federal courts.","start":1437.962,"stop":1443.377,"duration":5.41},{"text":"And additionally, I’d simply want to point out that there's nothing in the legislative history that shows an intent to modify the interests of justice standard which has long been attached to habeas corpus jurisdiction, and the District Judge in this very case deciding why would this determine the due process issue, indicated that it was in the interest of justice to do so.","start":1443.377,"stop":1475.38,"duration":32},{"text":"In other words, both the language, the policy, and the legislative history of this statute failed to suggest that Congress had any intention to change what had generally been understood to be the meaning of a four-four affirmance, a technical sort of response which is simply a way of disposing of the case that this Court could not decide.","start":1475.38,"stop":1507.288,"duration":31.91}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You would say then that it falls in the same category as a petition dismissed as improvidently granted?","start":1507.288,"stop":1515.071,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think by definite -- that question has long troubled me Mr. Chief Justice --","start":1515.071,"stop":1520.537,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll resume at that point in the morning Mr. Meltsner.","start":1520.537,"stop":1521.894,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1521.894,"stop":1524.386,"duration":2.49}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 19, 1972","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/17346","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, you have 19 minutes remaining.","start":0,"stop":3.213,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3.213,"stop":6.493,"duration":3.28},{"text":"In the time remaining, I would like to discuss petitioner’s challenge to the factual findings made by the district court with respect to the due process issue.","start":6.493,"stop":19.001,"duration":12.51},{"text":"Findings which were affirmed by the entire Court of Appeals below, that court dividing solely over the question of the consequence of the prior four to four affirmance in this case.","start":19.001,"stop":34.032,"duration":15.03},{"text":"But first, I would like to reply briefly to a question asked yesterday by Mr. Justice Rehnquist which I had either misheard or misunderstood.","start":34.032,"stop":44.61,"duration":10.58},{"text":"Justice Rehnquist asked me whether if this Court had in this case previously decided seven to two or nine to nothing against the respondent’s claim or whether res judicata would in that event had barred a subsequent federal habeas corpus petition and I answered yes, but I don’t think I gave a sufficiently distinct answer.","start":44.61,"stop":68.721,"duration":24.11},{"text":"I think, the answer is plainly with the statute involved in this case, 2244 (c) would in that event bar re-litigation and that is indeed the very situation, a very abuse of the writ which Congress was addressing itself to --","start":68.721,"stop":85.043,"duration":16.32}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You are addressing yourself yet, I suppose to the situation before the statute --","start":85.043,"stop":88.337,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I was.","start":88.337,"stop":88.865,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where you said the bill would have no equity but it’s not technically --","start":88.865,"stop":90.934,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s correct.","start":90.934,"stop":91.882,"duration":0.95},{"text":"I was answering you in terms of the Sanders' opinion, which was, of course, the backdrop against which 2244 (c) was drafted.","start":91.882,"stop":102.472,"duration":10.59},{"text":"Now, as I read the petitioner’s brief here and understand its argument yesterday, the state does not seriously contend that the district court define the standard of law which it had applied in this case incorrectly.","start":102.472,"stop":122.164,"duration":19.69},{"text":"What the district court did, was treat the showup as a suggestive and potentially dangerous identification device, but not one which was per se unconstitutional.","start":122.164,"stop":134.38,"duration":12.22},{"text":"It waived the showup and aggravating circumstances in this case against its necessity in this case and external indicia of reliability, whether there was anything which justified the use of the showup.","start":134.38,"stop":150.108,"duration":15.73},{"text":"And I think this conforms to what the Court in Curvy last term called weighing the prejudice to a defendant against society’s interest in law enforcement and it conforms almost identically to the analytic process which the Court itself used in Simmons versus the United States several terms ago nor do -- as I understand the State’s argument yesterday and its brief, nor does the state seriously challenge the application of this standard to the facts found by the district court and I will have hopefully something to say about that later.","start":150.108,"stop":189.8,"duration":39.69},{"text":"The state concentrates its attack here on the findings of fact made by the district court and as this Court generally does not reverse findings of historical fact, it seems to me quite plain that the state has a very heavy burden to carry.","start":189.8,"stop":212.81,"duration":23.01}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We do -- we do not hesitate to reverse them if they're clearly erroneous, do we?","start":212.81,"stop":218.781,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct Mr. Chief Justice and my -- a good deal of what I hope to say is --","start":218.781,"stop":221.409,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You are going to deal with ultimately rather glaring inconsistencies here?","start":221.409,"stop":228.183,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"And then that -- the question of support for the district court’s findings of fact is what I intend to turn to now.","start":228.183,"stop":236.607,"duration":8.42},{"text":"A preliminary matter, however, as I understood Mr. Durham yesterday, he said or implied that the district court’s findings were based on a cold record.","start":236.607,"stop":245.716,"duration":9.11},{"text":"They were based on the record made on direct review.","start":245.716,"stop":249.916,"duration":4.2},{"text":"That is simply not the case.","start":249.916,"stop":252.487,"duration":2.57},{"text":"The district court heard testimony from two police officers, including the police officer who is in-charge of the investigation of this case.","start":252.487,"stop":262.363,"duration":9.88},{"text":"He heard testimony from the prosecutors.","start":262.363,"stop":265.053,"duration":2.69},{"text":"He heard testimony from respondent’s mother and he heard expert testimony directed to the procedures used in this case.","start":265.053,"stop":273.169,"duration":8.12},{"text":"The testimony -- it appears in the appendix from pages 66 to 134.","start":273.169,"stop":280.321,"duration":7.15},{"text":"It amplified the record made on direct review, but it did more than that.","start":280.321,"stop":285.592,"duration":5.27},{"text":"It supplied the answers to many questions which this Court asked me in 1968 and I think that’s apparent from a reading of that section of the appendix.","start":285.592,"stop":297.691,"duration":12.1},{"text":"For example, the officer who was in-charge of the investigation, Captain McDaniel, testified to the efforts he used to put together a lineup in the four or so hours that he tried to do that.","start":297.691,"stop":321.09,"duration":23.4},{"text":"District court, after hearing his testimony which was directed to showing that he could not put a lineup together, rejected it.","start":321.09,"stop":330.833,"duration":9.74},{"text":"The testimony before the district judge dealt with the initial description given by the prosecutrix to the police shortly after the crime.","start":330.833,"stop":344.115,"duration":13.28},{"text":"That appears on page A-74.","start":344.115,"stop":346.953,"duration":2.84},{"text":"It deals with the question of voice identification where the prosecutrix according to the district judge, and as I will indicate later, or I hope to show later, there was a conflict between what she had testified to at trial and testified to before the district court.","start":346.953,"stop":366.004,"duration":19.05},{"text":"Finally, the expert witness gave us opinion of the procedures used in this case and clearly indicated that even an imperfect lineup, one where every trait of the person who was to be seen by the witness was not identical, was thought preferable in a showup.","start":366.004,"stop":389.204,"duration":23.2},{"text":"The district court relied on a good deal of this evidence and that appears on pages A-41 and A-42 of the record.","start":389.204,"stop":398.064,"duration":8.86},{"text":"So that there can be no question that the district court here was not of hearing oral testimony in weighing credibility.","start":398.064,"stop":409.643,"duration":11.58},{"text":"Now, before again talking about the factual findings that the state challenges, I think, I have to put it in perspective by indicating simply what the state does not challenge.","start":409.643,"stop":420.448,"duration":10.81},{"text":"The state does not challenge most of the factual conclusions reached by the district court.","start":420.448,"stop":426.07,"duration":5.62},{"text":"The state does not dispute that the evidence of the showup identification was admitted at trial that the showup took place between six and seven months after the crime that the police described respondent to the prosecutrix as a suspect before the identification, that the respondent was alone made to speak inflammatory words which was spoken by the assailant at the time of the crime, “Shut up or I’ll kill you” and that the prosecutrix relied to some extent on this voice identification.","start":426.07,"stop":465.375,"duration":39.31},{"text":"He testified before the district court that she identified him first before he spoke.","start":465.375,"stop":473.547,"duration":8.17},{"text":"But even she conceded that her identification was made more certain by what he said.","start":473.547,"stop":480.147,"duration":6.6},{"text":"At trial, of course, she said, in the state court, she said that the first thing that made her identify respondent was his voice, and this appears on page 17 of the record which was before this Court in 1968.","start":480.147,"stop":495.584,"duration":15.44},{"text":"It is also undisputed that there was no other evidence of guilt and identification evidence that the only other eyewitness to the events could not identify the respondent and that there was no independent photo identification in this case.","start":495.584,"stop":512.895,"duration":17.31},{"text":"So we come to the particular matters the state has concentrated its fire at.","start":512.895,"stop":522.361,"duration":9.47},{"text":"And as I read the brief and understand the argument, they are basically three.","start":522.361,"stop":527.615,"duration":5.25},{"text":"One; whether a truly concerted effort was made to hold the lineup in this case; secondly, the quality of the initial description given by the prosecutrix to the police shortly after the crime, and finally, the opportunity to observe at the time of the crime.","start":527.615,"stop":550.364,"duration":22.75},{"text":"And it is my submission that in each of these instances, there is sufficient evidence in the record so that no appellate tribunal can say that the district court -- district court’s findings as to these matters was clearly erroneous.","start":550.364,"stop":566.908,"duration":16.54},{"text":"For example, with respect to the holding in the district court that there was no truly concerted effort to hold the lineup in this case and no need for speed, the record shows that what this police officer did over the course of a morning in trying to rind -- round up a lineup was to check one jail facility and phone another, but not to go to visit.","start":566.908,"stop":594.709,"duration":27.8},{"text":"He did not try several other penal institutions that were located in the Nashville area, including the State Penitentiary and that there was absolutely no need for speed in this case.","start":594.709,"stop":608.731,"duration":14.02},{"text":"The crime was seven months old and the complaining witness had been perfectly cooperative in the past with the police.","start":608.731,"stop":619.804,"duration":11.07},{"text":"The district court had a good deal of knowledge about local conditions.","start":619.804,"stop":624.572,"duration":4.77},{"text":"He heard the police officer testify in explanation of why he did not put together a lineup and concluded that there was no need for such a prompt showup in this case.","start":624.572,"stop":641.406,"duration":16.83},{"text":"Secondly, with respect to the initial opportunity to observe at the time of the crime, district court held, and this appears on A-41 of the appendix that the prosecutrix clearly did not have a good opportunity.","start":641.406,"stop":659.085,"duration":17.68},{"text":"Well, she, in fact, testified that she saw the rapist, but the objective circumstances certainly support the district court’s conclusion.","start":659.085,"stop":669.781,"duration":10.7},{"text":"She was grabbed from behind in an unlit hallway, marched out through an unlit kitchen, up on some railroad tracks where there was some light from the moon and some overhead lights from the nearby street, but she marched along these railroad tracks at the point of a knife.","start":669.781,"stop":693.428,"duration":23.65},{"text":"And she was marched along those tracks for a block or two and then pushed into some overgrowth where the crime was -- where the crime took place and then the assailant fled.","start":693.428,"stop":704.787,"duration":11.36},{"text":"Now, given those circumstances, and the prosecutrix’s admission before the district court on page A-125 that the lighting in her house was dim, it seems to me that this is not a matter where this Court can possibly substitute its judgment as to the opportunity to view the assailant for the district courts.","start":704.787,"stop":733.485,"duration":28.7},{"text":"The third issue has to do with the quality of the initial description given to the police at the time of the crime by the woman who had been raped.","start":733.485,"stop":744.22,"duration":10.74},{"text":"And here, the evidence before the district court is quite clear, although at the time of trial, Mrs. Beamer, the woman who’d been raped, listed a number of traits.","start":744.22,"stop":759.634,"duration":15.41},{"text":"She described them as the traits which led her to identify the man which she identified, the respondent, at the time of the pretrial identification.","start":759.634,"stop":771.477,"duration":11.84},{"text":"There was no evidence in the record which told us what sort of a description she’d given seven months earlier to the police.","start":771.477,"stop":780.805,"duration":9.33},{"text":"Well, before the district court on page A-74, Captain McDaniel, the chief officer involved in the case was asked about this specifically and he testified referring to his notes, “Alright, sir, says, his height was six feet tall, 180 pounds, he was dark hair, medium or medium to dark complexion.”","start":780.805,"stop":809.22,"duration":28.42},{"text":"That was the description given by the prosecutrix to the police according to this officer’s notes.","start":809.22,"stop":815.799,"duration":6.58},{"text":"Now in light of that, again it seems to me that it cannot be said that the district court’s holding that the initial description was general can anyway be off set as clearly erroneous.","start":815.799,"stop":836.845,"duration":21.05},{"text":"That brings me to a last issue which is merely the application of a standard which I take not to be seriously disputed to facts which I do not think this Court properly sets aside and, I think, any examination of what lower courts have done with Stovall and any examination of the decision of this Court which goes into application of Stovall in most detail that being Simmons will demonstrate that the district court properly applied the standard to the facts.","start":836.845,"stop":882.209,"duration":45.36},{"text":"I think, looking at Simmons is quite constructive.","start":882.209,"stop":885.784,"duration":3.58},{"text":"In that case, the identification procedure which was a photo identification was upheld, but looking at the factors used in Justice Harlan’s analysis in that case, we find that they are almost identical to the factors used in analyzing this case by the district court and inferentially by the Court of Appeals.","start":885.784,"stop":909.473,"duration":23.69},{"text":"In Simmons, the Court’s opinion talks about the necessity for a prompt photo identification.","start":909.473,"stop":917.353,"duration":7.88},{"text":"Here, there was absolutely no necessity for a showup, roughly seven months after the crime with the cooperative witness.","start":917.353,"stop":925.363,"duration":8.01},{"text":"In Simmons, the Court talks about the initial opportunity to observe a well-lighted bank.","start":925.363,"stop":932.166,"duration":6.8},{"text":"Here, we have a dark house, woods and moonlight.","start":932.166,"stop":935.631,"duration":3.46},{"text":"In Simmons, the Court talks about fresh memories.","start":935.631,"stop":939.259,"duration":3.63},{"text":"Here, we have a stale memory and a stale memory in part at least of a voice.","start":939.259,"stop":945.459,"duration":6.2},{"text":"In Simmons, there was no suggestion whatsoever by the FBI agents that the man whose photo they showed along with other photos was under suspicion.","start":945.459,"stop":956.286,"duration":10.83},{"text":"Here, the police described Biggers to the prosecutrix as a suspect reinforcing with an official finger of what the showup itself did which was to point that the respondent as a person who the police thought may will have been guilty.","start":956.286,"stop":981.787,"duration":25.5},{"text":"And finally, in Simmons, there were five eyewitnesses who all identified the defendant.","start":981.787,"stop":991.688,"duration":9.9},{"text":"Here the only other witness to the crime did not and the only evidence of guilt was the identification which we would assert is tainted.","start":991.688,"stop":1005.114,"duration":13.43},{"text":"Now, four years ago, Mr. Justice White asked me if I was merely asking the Court to rule that there was no evidence before the jury in this case.","start":1005.114,"stop":1017.115,"duration":12},{"text":"Since that argument, the Court in Simmons and in Foster has clearly indicated that the procedures employed by the state in taking identification evidence can be so defective as to bar their admission as a matter of law.","start":1017.115,"stop":1037.726,"duration":20.61},{"text":"This is the principle we rely upon here today and submit it was properly applied by the courts below.","start":1037.726,"stop":1045.51,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Meltsner, at page 18 of your brief you have a statement, “she did not identify the defendant until after the voice test.”","start":1045.51,"stop":1053.714,"duration":8.2},{"text":"Now, what's the record on that?","start":1053.714,"stop":1057.478,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 18?","start":1057.478,"stop":1057.967,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 18, yes.","start":1057.967,"stop":1061.869,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"“She did not finally identify the defendant until after a voice test.”","start":1061.869,"stop":1065.671,"duration":3.8},{"text":"That is at page 129 of the appendix Mr. Chief Justice and if I may just direct myself to that in more detail, in making that assertion we are giving the state’s arguments as much weight as it will bear.","start":1065.671,"stop":1078.346,"duration":12.67},{"text":"Our contention is -- and the district court did not resolve this conflict, that much of the evidence at trial suggested that she identified him only after he spoke.","start":1078.346,"stop":1088.452,"duration":10.11},{"text":"She said so herself on page A-17, in a statement on page R-17 and the statement by a police officer on R-66 confirms this and the respondent himself said that she did not identify him until after he spoke.","start":1088.452,"stop":1104.841,"duration":16.39},{"text":"Four years later, she was certain that she had identified him -- she did -- certain that she identified him before he spoke not after he spoke.","start":1104.841,"stop":1115.019,"duration":10.18},{"text":"But I then asked her, “Well after he said, 'Shut up or I’ll kill you,' were you more certain of your identification?”","start":1115.019,"stop":1121.29,"duration":6.27},{"text":"And she said, “Yes.”","start":1121.29,"stop":1124.728,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Then this is followed by the statement, “The district court found that she failed to identify him at the trial.”","start":1124.728,"stop":1131.779,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s correct.","start":1131.779,"stop":1132.763,"duration":0.98},{"text":"The district court --","start":1132.763,"stop":1133.749,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Did she make --","start":1133.749,"stop":1133.986,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"The district court said there was great doubt that there was an in-court identification in this case.","start":1133.986,"stop":1139.524,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But what do you think the record -- the appendix of the trial court shows on that?","start":1139.524,"stop":1146.439,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"The appendix at -- before the district court should testify that she did identify him four years earlier at trial, all the record of the trial shows is that she was asked, “Is there any doubt in your mind today?”","start":1146.439,"stop":1159.334,"duration":12.89},{"text":"And she said, “No.","start":1159.334,"stop":1160.166,"duration":0.83},{"text":"There's no doubt in my mind today.”","start":1160.166,"stop":1161.768,"duration":1.6},{"text":"No, that is not the way --","start":1161.768,"stop":1163.272,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that a -- is that a good identification?","start":1163.272,"stop":1165.21,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because I think -- because identifying someone in a courtroom is a question of kicking them out from the group, I am not saying that there is no doubt.","start":1165.21,"stop":1173.268,"duration":8.06},{"text":"But in any event, this case must be reversed because the -- almost the entire state’s case was the out-of-court identification and testimony about it, not the in-court identification.","start":1173.268,"stop":1185.996,"duration":12.73},{"text":"And Foster versus California is a decision of the court which reverses on that basis even though there was an in-court identification.","start":1185.996,"stop":1195.937,"duration":9.94}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Meltsner, going back to the relevance of this Court’s earlier action for a moment, would you agree that in view of the statute, the earlier decisions of this Court such as United States against Pink and the Durham case which makes some comment on the effect of four to four affirmance in non-habeas corpus situations are perhaps relevant in construing the meaning that Congress intended to use when it said actually adjudicate even though they -- those cases didn’t deal with habeas corpus?","start":1195.937,"stop":1233.659,"duration":37.72}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, to the -- to the extent that they indicate that the process of direct review is over, I suppose they're relevant.","start":1233.659,"stop":1244.005,"duration":10.35},{"text":"But I think the -- there's nothing in the legislative history or anything in those cases or anything that I can immediately think of in logic that would alter the scope of the writ in this case.","start":1244.005,"stop":1258.836,"duration":14.83},{"text":"And in anyway, act conclusively, to bar federal habeas corpus.","start":1258.836,"stop":1264.391,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except you’ve conceded in effect that the statute has changed the situation at least after a seven to two affirmance by this Court, so the statute did alter the scope of the writ in that sense.","start":1264.391,"stop":1277.567,"duration":13.18}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"In that sense, it did.","start":1277.567,"stop":1280.328,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Meltsner, would the situation had been any different on the seven to two affirmance if we never had a statute?","start":1280.328,"stop":1287.105,"duration":6.78}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"If we didn’t have a statute?","start":1287.105,"stop":1288.445,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1288.445,"stop":1290.378,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"My -- that brings me back to the answer to Mr. Justice Rehnquist’s question yesterday.","start":1290.378,"stop":1296.634,"duration":6.26},{"text":"In that event, I think a district judge clearly would have the power not to entertain the writ.","start":1296.634,"stop":1302.676,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1302.676,"stop":1303.564,"duration":0.89},{"text":"So it has a presidential [Attempt to Laughter] -- has presidential value.","start":1303.564,"stop":1307.323,"duration":3.76},{"text":"So in that sense, the statute adds nothing to the situation as regards the impact of an affirmance here, nine to nothing or seven to two--","start":1307.323,"stop":1316.104,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":1316.104,"stop":1316.282,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that disposes adversely to the state prisoner his constitutional claim.","start":1316.282,"stop":1321.477,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the real meaning of statute is in its definition of when in that instance, one can still go back --","start":1321.477,"stop":1327.874,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This is not a problem of res judicata?","start":1327.874,"stop":1332.909,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Michael Meltsner","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1332.909,"stop":1335.01,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Durham, you have about 16 minutes left.","start":1335.01,"stop":1340.291,"duration":5.28}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I’ll try not to use all of those Your Honor.","start":1340.291,"stop":1342.419,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1342.419,"stop":1343.482,"duration":1.06},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1343.482,"stop":1346.519,"duration":3.04},{"text":"I will go directly to the Court -- about the dispute – the factual dispute between my adversary and me all along.","start":1346.519,"stop":1357.553,"duration":11.03},{"text":"We seem to read these records differently.","start":1357.553,"stop":1359.635,"duration":2.08},{"text":"I just amended to a go Mr. Meltsner said on page 17 of the original trial record which unfortunately Your Honors don’t have, there's only one copy in the Supreme Court library.","start":1359.635,"stop":1371.55,"duration":11.91},{"text":"We were allowed to use the original record that -- this says that the lady was identified first by voice and I’m reading here on page 17, “What physical characteristics, if any, caused you to be able to identify him?”","start":1371.55,"stop":1387.288,"duration":15.74},{"text":"The answer --","start":1387.288,"stop":1387.559,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This is -- as at the trial -- at the original trial in the state court?","start":1387.559,"stop":1391.593,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1391.593,"stop":1393.291,"duration":1.7},{"text":"Counsel referred to this just a moment ago and the answer to that question is, “First of all, his size; next, I could remember his voice.”","start":1393.291,"stop":1406.273,"duration":12.98},{"text":"Then counsel cited Your Honors to page 66 of the same record which he says that this was her identification of him first by his voice, was confirmed by the policeman, at that particular time Lt. McDaniel.","start":1406.273,"stop":1425.576,"duration":19.3},{"text":"I’m looking at page 66, said -- the question of the police officer was, “And when did that take place?”","start":1425.576,"stop":1444.995,"duration":19.42},{"text":"Right at that time when she, damn, and he doesn’t get to finish that word, he says, “Saw him, she asked us to have him repeat the question which he repeated, that, and she also by voice.”","start":1444.995,"stop":1460.513,"duration":15.52},{"text":"Yes sir, well, that’s ambiguous, as I point on my brief.","start":1460.513,"stop":1464.656,"duration":4.14},{"text":"The three offices testified about the identification whether or not it was voice first or after, didn’t make any constitutional difference in 1965; two, he said she identified him first and this one man whose testimony is so ambiguous, it doesn’t even make a grammatical sentence in the English language, they seize on certain words of that, at this page 66, and try to say that this officer said that she identified him first by voice.","start":1464.656,"stop":1495.747,"duration":31.09},{"text":"We respectfully disagree.","start":1495.747,"stop":1500.067,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the basic point as I understood it that your Brother was making was that all his testimony went to the circumstances under which she identified him at the lineup prior to, he is talking about the showup, prior to the trial and that she did not identify him at the trial independently.","start":1500.067,"stop":1524.225,"duration":24.16},{"text":"I think, that was the basic point your Brother was making, perhaps, I misunderstood it.","start":1524.225,"stop":1528.822,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I respectfully disagree, Your Honor.","start":1528.822,"stop":1531.47,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You disagree that’s the point he was making?","start":1531.47,"stop":1533.012,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I disagree if that was the point.","start":1533.012,"stop":1534.482,"duration":1.47},{"text":"I understood the point to be that he’s trying to show that this was a weak identification and the voice wasn’t heard as a mode of identification.","start":1534.482,"stop":1542.351,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he said that.","start":1542.351,"stop":1543.305,"duration":0.95},{"text":"But I thought -- I understood his--","start":1543.305,"stop":1545.208,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"I also -- I understand and I agree with you Your Honor --","start":1545.208,"stop":1546.715,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- basic point to be that there was not an independent identification in the courtroom at the time of the trial and all of this testimony went to the identification prior to the trial at the -- during the procedures that he says were constitutionally invalid.","start":1546.715,"stop":1563.674,"duration":16.96}]},{"speakerName":"Bart C. Durham, III","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, my colleague says that the -- I have said that the district court made findings on a cold record and he disagrees with this.","start":1563.674,"stop":1576.177,"duration":12.5},{"text":"What I am saying, and I want this to be clear, is that take the cold record of this trial in 1965 here and take -- supplement that with the very limited evidentiary hearing in which the two police officers testified adversely to Mr. Meltsner’s position and no one testified that I know of to his position.","start":1576.177,"stop":1601.766,"duration":25.59},{"text":"And Mrs. Beamer testified adversely to his position, but just doesn't believe them entirely and just go on the cold record.","start":1601.766,"stop":1613.483,"duration":11.72},{"text":"In other words, believe all of his witnesses before the district -- United States’ district judge, disbelieved all of my witnesses before the United States’ district judge and my assertion is that the record is still un-contradicted as to (a) the lady did not change her testimony between the time of the trial and the time of the habeas corpus hearing nor did the police officers.","start":1613.483,"stop":1639.524,"duration":26.04},{"text":"The point being that they -- the constitutional point that they are anxious to convey is that it puts them in a better constitutional posture if they can have it so that she identified him first by voice and then by recognition of the person and made no constitutional difference back then -- back in that time.","start":1639.524,"stop":1662.727,"duration":23.2},{"text":"So, the district judge found that the police officer and the lady changed their testimony.","start":1662.727,"stop":1668.471,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Now, I’m saying that that is un-contradicted in the record that district judge errs there.","start":1668.471,"stop":1678.032,"duration":9.56},{"text":"Now, counsel mentioned the finding according to appendix 41 of the district judge’s order, there's no indication that a truly concerted effort was made to produce suitable subjects for a lineup aside from a phone call to the juvenile home and a screening of metro jail inmates, no other efforts were made.","start":1678.032,"stop":1698.859,"duration":20.83},{"text":"All the testimony at the habeas corpus hearing went into that and the district judge, we say, just ignored that.","start":1698.859,"stop":1706.508,"duration":7.65},{"text":"Now, I suppose, you would have to not disbelieve that or perhaps that finding would stand.","start":1706.508,"stop":1712.096,"duration":5.59},{"text":"Their only testimonial was that this police officer said, “I consulted with a juvenile court judge and his superior to jail and it wasn’t possible to find anyone of that size.”","start":1712.096,"stop":1726.221,"duration":14.13},{"text":"The picture of Mr. Biggers, all of them have introduced into evidence is a part of the original trial record.","start":1726.221,"stop":1732.768,"duration":6.55},{"text":"He’s a large boy, he was only three days past his 16th birthday but he’s a giant, sort of young man, and the state argued that it was -- that -- they -- extremely difficult to get young people that large or people that large who would be that young.","start":1732.768,"stop":1752.943,"duration":20.17},{"text":"He’s -- he stand that up -- they’d stand that in -- either because of their age or because of their size.","start":1752.943,"stop":1760.219,"duration":7.28},{"text":"He’s a giant, 16-year-old, whose -- who has a very distinctive appearance.","start":1760.219,"stop":1769.88,"duration":9.66},{"text":"Counsel cited you to a statement that Mrs. -- that the victim, Mrs. Beamer made, cite you to page 125 of the record where she says that her lighting in the house was dim.","start":1769.88,"stop":1784.426,"duration":14.55},{"text":"Well, if you want to just go through this thing and -- on cross-examination and say well, was your light kind of dim, or something like that, you can find that, but take the thing as a whole.","start":1784.426,"stop":1796.735,"duration":12.31},{"text":"Take the testimony as a whole, in many other places and at the trial, she said that it was -- the house was, “Well lighted.”","start":1796.735,"stop":1806.648,"duration":9.91},{"text":"And then went into that in some degree.","start":1806.648,"stop":1810.127,"duration":3.48},{"text":"We think that the argument of course is that the jury’s verdict has to a great degree settled that.","start":1810.127,"stop":1822.993,"duration":12.87},{"text":"The -- I realize we do have a burden here that -- not an easy one to overturn factual findings.","start":1822.993,"stop":1833.537,"duration":10.54},{"text":"The findings were as counsel stated affirmed by the Sixth Circuit but to seek -- they would -- were done out of hand as I’ve argued earlier, first reason, the state didn’t raise much of an issue about the findings of the fact in the Sixth Circuit.","start":1833.537,"stop":1849.027,"duration":15.49},{"text":"We’ve reserved it but we didn’t go -- I wouldn’t counsel then.","start":1849.027,"stop":1853.259,"duration":4.23},{"text":"Frankly, we didn’t argue that as strenuously as we did the legal argument.","start":1853.259,"stop":1858.274,"duration":5.01},{"text":"All the Sixth Circuit said it was, we’re not able to say that this was clearly erroneous.","start":1858.274,"stop":1864.37,"duration":6.1},{"text":"We are, I am able to tell Your Honors that the finding of the district judge is clearly erroneous in seven aspects, and I’ve listed them in my brief.","start":1864.37,"stop":1885.955,"duration":21.59},{"text":"Counsel has analogized Biggers to Stovall, Simmons and some of the other identification cases which this Court has decided and I frankly believe that there's little profit in there.","start":1885.955,"stop":1899.863,"duration":13.91},{"text":"I think that the -- and counsel said that, I had no dispute with the district judge’s interpretation of what the law leads and that’s probably true.","start":1899.863,"stop":1908.833,"duration":8.97},{"text":"I think, the district judge just as every judge and as this Court in light of Stovall says, “Was the man prejudiced by this identification?","start":1908.833,"stop":1920.204,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Was it an improper identification?","start":1920.204,"stop":1923.012,"duration":2.81},{"text":"Was it unfair that basically it’s what it boils down to?”","start":1923.012,"stop":1926.951,"duration":3.94},{"text":"If it’s unfair, so unfair as to deny him a fair trial, let’s give him a new trial.","start":1926.951,"stop":1933.188,"duration":6.24},{"text":"And the state respectfully contends that the totality of the testimony, the undisputed testimony that he did get a fair trial.","start":1933.188,"stop":1947.031,"duration":13.84},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":1947.031,"stop":1950.248,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you gentlemen.","start":1950.248,"stop":1951.257,"duration":1.01},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":1951.257,"stop":1954.271,"duration":3.01}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Oct  18 - 19, 1972","petitioner":"William S. Neil, Warden of the Tennessee State Penitentiary","respondent":"Archie Nathaniel Biggers","docket":"71-586","citation":"409 US 188 (1972)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/409/188","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit","grantedOn":"Feb 28, 1972","decidedOn":"Dec 6, 1972"}